## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Pattern Classification

This is **Timeout enforcement** + **ThreadAbortException as control flow**. Three APIs that throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` / `SYSLIB0006` in .NET 6+:

| Dead API | Replacement |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### If `work` is long-running and must respond to cancellation

The above stops *waiting*, but the delegate keeps running in the background. To make work actually stop, pass the token through:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    try
    {
        var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Caller must cooperate:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| **Work doesn't actually stop** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cancellation is *cooperative*. If `work` never checks the token, it runs to completion in the background even after timeout. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks timers. Always `using`. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish timeout from external cancellation. |
| **Blocking on async code inside `work`** | Can deadlock if there's a `SynchronizationContext`. Prefer `async Task` overloads end-to-end. |
| **Uncooperative third-party code** | If you can't modify `work` to accept a token, the fire-and-forget `Task.Run` version is your only option — or move the work to a child `Process` and call `Process.Kill()`. |

### Behavioral Difference

| Behavior | .NET Framework (original) | .NET 8 (migrated) |
|---|---|---|
| Thread termination | Forcible via `ThreadAbortException` injection | Cooperative — code must check token |
| Timeout accuracy | Approximate (abort is async) | Precise (`WaitAsync` returns immediately) |
| Resource cleanup | Risky — abort can corrupt state mid-operation | Safe — cancellation only at checkpoints |
| `finally` blocks | Always run (even after abort) | Always run (normal exception flow) |
